ue on the ballot passed amendments banning the practice, and the subject soon dropped off the media’s radar. This pattern of waxing and waning in the public eye has characterized the debate over same-sex marriage since 1996 and the passing of the Defense of Marriage Act. Since then, court rulings and local legislatures have kept the issue alive in the political sphere, and conservatives and gay rights advocates have made the issue a key battlefield in the culture wars. The Politics of Same-Sex Marriage brings together an esteemed list of scholars to explore all facets of this heated issue, including the ideologies and strategies on both sides of the argument, the public’s response, the use of the issue in political campaigns, and how same-sex marriage fits into the broad context of policy cycles and windows of political opportunity. With comprehensive coverage from a variety of different approaches, this volume will be a vital sourcebook for activists, politicians, and scholars alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArts. 0aPolitical science. 0aPopular music. 0aSame-sex marriagexPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aSame-sex marriagezUnited States. 0aSame-sex marriage. 0aSocial sciences. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asame-sex marriage, homosexuality, supreme court, gay, lesbian, sexuality, lgbt, lgbtq, lgbtqia, ballot, amendments, politics, political science, nonfiction, doma, culture wars, campaigns, policy, civil union, rights, domestic partnership, religion, government, public opinion, values, litigation, legislation, history, presidency, congress.1 aBrewer, Paul R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCahill, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, David C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato